The Limit of Panic
Copenhagen — We often hear that the world we know will come to an end, usually described as ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Roman Club published the seminal "Limits to Growth" more than forty years ago, its basic idea has been with us ever since.
But time is not forgiving.
The "Limits to Growth" of 1972 warned humanity that catastrophic collapse was imminent.
However, what we saw afterwards was financial panic, but not any real shortages or production collapses.
On the contrary, resources created by human ingenuity were more than sufficient to meet human consumption.
Nevertheless, the basic idea of "The Limits to Growth" still holds: we continue a trend, preoccupied with misleading solutions to minor issues, while neglecting major problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, technological optimism faded, the Vietnam War became a disaster, societies fell into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" sparked panic about pollution and ignited the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 title "The Population Bomb" said it all.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were pessimistic.
The intention of "Limits to Growth" was to make people worry about resource depletion.
This was our fate, because too many people wanted to consume too much.
Even if our genius won us some time, in the end we would destroy the Earth and ourselves through pollution.
The only hope was to halt economic growth itself, reduce consumption, recycle, and force people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at a significantly poorer level than now.
This view still resonates today, despite being profoundly wrong.
For example, the authors of The Limits to Growth predicted that by 2013, the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc.
However, although commodity prices have recently rebounded, overall they have fallen to one-third of the levels of 150 years ago.
Technological innovation has replaced mercury in batteries, dental materials, and thermometers, and by 2000, mercury consumption had dropped by 98%, and its price had fallen by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, supplies of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc have exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new refining technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally expected to be depleted by 1990 and 1992 respectively; today, reserves of both are higher than the 1970 levels, despite our greatly increased consumption.
Over the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas reserves of the United States and halved the price.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14 times this century, with developing countries increasing 24 times.
The reason "Limits to Growth" was wrong is that the authors overlooked the greatest resource: our own ingenuity.
Population growth has slowed since the 1960s.
The food supply has not collapsed (1.5 billion hectares of arable land are being used, and in addition there are 2.7 billion hectares of reserves).
The rate of malnutrition has been cut by more than half, dropping from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution has not defeated us either.
The Club of Rome imagined a pastoral past when we had no air pollution with suspended particles, and were happy farmers, and in the future, heating chimneys would make it impossible for us to breathe. The reality is completely the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, but nearly 3 million people — one in every 500 — died each year from air pollution, most of which was indoor air pollution.
Now, this ratio has dropped to one death per 2000 people.
Although the number of deaths caused by pollution is still higher than that of malaria, its mortality rate is declining rather than increasing.
Nevertheless, the ideas fostered by "The Limits to Growth" continue to influence the thinking of the public and elites.
Take recycling, for example; it is usually just a feel-good gesture that costs the environment a lot with little benefit.
For instance, paper usually comes from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The procedures related to paper recycling and government subsidies result in low-quality paper, protecting resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, fears of overpopulation have led to self-defeating policies, such as China's family planning and India's compulsory sterilization.
Moreover, although pesticides and other pollutants are believed to kill half of the human population, effective pesticide regulation results in only 20 deaths per year in the United States, while the use of pesticides has created cheaper and more abundant food supplies.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — a movement fueled by pesticide panic — would add an extra $100 billion annually to the United States.
Agricultural efficiency would decrease by 16%, and to maintain current output, an additional 65 million hectares of farmland would need to be cultivated — equivalent to half the area of modern-day California.
Rising prices will lead to a decline in the consumption of fruits and vegetables, causing serious negative health impacts (including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer-related deaths each year).
Being addicted to dark scenarios prevents us from paying attention to real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, and easily curable diseases still cause 15 million deaths each year — equivalent to a quarter of the total number of deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people are freed from poverty, most can afford the burden of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past three decades, 680 million people in China have escaped poverty, leading the world in reducing the population living in poverty by nearly one billion.
This has brought about widespread improvements in health, life expectancy, and quality of life.
The forty-year history since the publication of "The Limits to Growth" shows that we need more growth, not less.
It is estimated that the expansion of trade can bring over $10 trillion in annual benefits by the end of this century, and these benefits far exceed those of the timid "safe" policies that promote fear.
But this requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and using our boundless potential to create a brighter future.
